<refnamediv><indexterm><primary sortas="migrate-timers">migrate-timers &mdash; moves a timer when a server instance stops</primary></indexterm><indexterm><primary sortas="moves a timer when a server instance stops">moves a timer when a server instance stops &mdash; migrate-timers</primary></indexterm>
<refname>migrate-timers</refname><refpurpose>moves a timer when a server instance stops</refpurpose></refnamediv>
<refsynopsisdiv><title>&synp-tt;</title>
<cmdsynopsis><command>migrate-timers</command><arg choice="plain">&synopsis-common;<arg choice="opt">&Dash;&Dash;destination <replaceable>destination_server_name</replaceable></arg></arg><arg choice="plain"><replaceable>server_name</replaceable></arg>
</cmdsynopsis></refsynopsisdiv>
<refsect1><title>&desc-tt;</title>
<para>The function of the <command>migrate-timers</command> command is to move the timer to a specified server, when the server instance stops or fails abnormally. This command is supported in remote mode only.</para>
</refsect1>
<refsect1><title>&opts-tt;</title>
<variablelist termlength="medium">&options-common;
<varlistentry><term><option role="nodash">&Dash;&Dash;destination</option></term><listitem><para>This is the destination server instance. If this option is not specified, then DAS will find a server instance or multiple server instances. A migration notification will be sent to the selected server instances.
</para>
</listitem></varlistentry>
</variablelist></refsect1>
<refsect1><title>&oper-tt;</title>
<variablelist termlength="medium">
<varlistentry><term><replaceable>server_name</replaceable></term><listitem><para>This is the current location of the server instance. The server instance should not be active during this process.</para>
</listitem></varlistentry>
</variablelist></refsect1>
<refsect1><title>&exam-tt;</title>
<example>
<title>Using migrate-timers</title>
<para>This is a simple example of how to use the command.</para>
<screen>asadmin><userinput>migrate-timers --servername dance</userinput>
This command was successfully executed.</screen>
</example>
</refsect1>
